^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|I very much like leading ^*Bthe queen from ace-king-queen^*N at suit contracts. Partner may not know immediately what you have done. But if the jack is in dummy or in partner's hand, he will recognize it. I hope you don't lead the queen from queen doubleton unless partner has bid the suit.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^b@2
^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|There are potential ambiguities and problems when leading this way, but I believe in the long run it is the right way to go in suit contracts. Notrump contracts are another story. It is standard for experienced players to lead the queen from king-queen-ten-nine in notrump. This tells partner to drop the jack. But with ace-king-queen-fourth, you don't want partner to drop the jack. So be careful. The moral of the story is that we hope you get to lead from ace-king-queen frequently. But in reality you won't. |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^b@2
^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|When you lead the ace from ace-king partner is supposed to signal attitude. One of the potential advantages of leading queen from ace-king-queen is that partner no longer has to give you an attitude signal if he can see the jack. Both you and he know that he doesn't have strength in the suit. So I like partner to signal suit preference. |
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


